Basic Cloud Services Used (The "Notes" Section)

While I mentioned high-end services like Spanner, the "bread and butter" of the app relies on these foundational services:

A. Compute: AWS EC2 / Google Compute Engine
Usage: This is where the actual game "Room" lives. When you enter a match, a small portion of an EC2 instance is carved out for your 50-player group.
Instance Type: They usually use C5 or C6g (Graviton) instances. These are "Compute Optimized" because game logic needs high-speed single-core performance
more than it needs lots of slow cores.

B. Storage: AWS S3 / Google Cloud Storage
Usage: S3 is not used during the match (it's too slow). It’s used to store Static Assets.
Examples: All the character skins, weapon textures, and map files are stored as "Blobs" in S3. When the game checks for an update, 
it pulls these files from S3 and sends them to the CDN (Content Delivery Network) for you to download.

C. Database: AWS RDS / DynamoDB
Usage: Managing the player's "State."
RDS (Relational): Used for things that need "Transactions," like buying Diamonds. You can't have a crash halfway through a purchase, so RDS ensures the data
is written perfectly.
DynamoDB (NoSQL): Used for the Leaderboard and Friend Lists. It is incredibly fast at reading simple "Key-Value" data (e.g., "What is PlayerX's rank?").


D. Memory: AWS ElastiCache (Redis)
Usage: The "Session" store.
Details: When you are in the lobby, the server needs to know you are "Online." Checking a hard drive (S3/RDS) every second is too slow.
ElastiCache keeps this info in RAM, allowing the server to handle millions of "Online/Offline" status checks per second.


E. Elastic Load Balancing (ALB/NLB)
Usage: When millions of players hit "Login" at the same time, the Load Balancer acts like a traffic cop. It distributes the login requests across 100+ different
login servers so no single server crashes.

F. Amazon SNS / SES (Simple Notification/Email)
Usage: These are used for Push Notifications.
Example: When the "New Mystery Shop is Live!" notification pops up on your phone, it’s being triggered by SNS.

G. CloudWatch / Prometheus
Usage: Monitoring & Alerting.
Details: If a server in South America starts lagging or its CPU hits 95%, CloudWatch sends an automatic alert to Garena’s "NOC" (Network Operations Center) 
so they can fix it before players notice.
